[[File:Kamo 001.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Torii gate]]
'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Takatsuki City|Q335423|qid=Q335423|1=Takatsuki}}, Osaka Prefecture. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, and under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was classified as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The current enshrined deities are as follows<ref>The enshrined deities are based on [http://kamojinja.web.fc2.com/kamojinja01.html History of Kamo Shrine] (official website). Ōyamatsumi-no-Mikoto is treated as a deity of special status among them, according to the same site and the shrine register displayed within the precincts.</ref>.
* '''{{ill|qid=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi|Q386563|qid=Q386563|qid=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōyamatsumi}}'''
* {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|qid=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi}}
* {{ill|lt=Izanami|Q682306|qid=Q682306|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami}}
* {{ill|lt=Kamo Taketsunumi-no-Mikoto|Q11634939|qid=Q11634939|lt=Kamo no Mioya Ōkami|1=Kamotaketsunumi no Mikoto}}

Various documents such as the “Shrine Register” list the enshrined deity as Ōyamatsumi-no-Kami, but as described below, according to the theory that identifies this shrine as the Shikinaisha Mishima Kamo Shrine, the enshrined deity is considered to be the ancestral deity of the Kamo clan<ref name="place"/>. In addition, since this area was a place where the Mishima Agatanushi held power, there is also a theory that regards their ancestral deity as the enshrined deity<ref name="place"/>. The “{{ill|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|Q1045362|qid=Q1045362|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}” records that the Mishima no Sukune (descendants of the Mishima Agatanushi, Jingibetsu of the Right Capital) and the Kamo Agatanushi (Jingibetsu of Yamashiro Province) share the same ancestor<ref name="place"/>.

=== History ===
=== Foundation ===
The date of foundation is unknown. According to shrine tradition, it was originally established by the resident Kamo clan, and later came to be known as “Mishima Kamo Shrine” because the immigrant Mishima clan rose to power in the area<ref>[http://kamojinja.web.fc2.com/kamojinja03.html The original tutelary deity of Settsu–Mishima] (official website).</ref>.

=== Historical overview ===
In the mid-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, the “{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}” lists “Mishima Kamo Shrine, Shimashimo District, Settsu Province” as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}. Since Yukihiko Ambo pointed out in “Historical Sites and Scenic Places of Mishima District” that the “Osaka Prefecture Shrine Register” states: “Although there are no old records, it has long been handed down that the enshrined deity is Ōyamatsumi-no-Mikoto; the place of enshrinement was formerly called Shimashimo District (this village was originally in Shimashimo District and was incorporated into Shimakami District during the Tokugawa era) … it has also been popularly called Mishima Kamo, Go-i Kamo Shrine, or Mishima Shrine,” this shrine has been regarded as one of the {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} for the Engishiki Mishima Kamo Shrine.

Another candidate shrine for the Shikinaisha is {{ill|lt=Mishima Kamo Shrine|Q11355295|qid=Q11355295|1=Mishima-Kamo Shrine}} located in Mishimae. Since Mishima Kamo Shrine lies within {{ill|lt=Shimakami District|Q10965808|qid=Q10965808|1=Shimakami district}}, this shrine is considered more plausible in terms of district boundaries<ref name="place">“Place Names of Osaka Prefecture,” entry on Kamo Shrine.</ref>. On the other hand, an excerpt from the “Iyo Province Fudoki” records that Ōyamatsumi-no-Kami moved from “Mishima of Tsukushi Province” to Iyo, and since the deity is also called the “God of the Crossing,” it has been argued that Kamo Shrine, which is distant from rivers, does not fit this description<ref>Matsushita Akira, “Mishima Kamo Shrine,” in Ken’ichi Tanigawa (ed.), “Gods of Japan – Shrines and Sacred Sites – Vol. 3: Settsu, Kawachi, Izumi, Awaji” ({{ill|lt=Hakusuisha|Q4346470|qid=Q4346470|1=Hakusuisha Publishing}}).</ref>. In any case, no definitive conclusion has been reached.

At the end of the Heian period, it is said that {{ill|lt=Emperor Go-Shirakawa|Q317984|qid=Q317984|1=Emperor Go-Shirakawa}}’s consort {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kenreimon-in|1=UNKNOWN}} prayed at “Mishima Shrine” for the birth of a prince<ref name="ka1">[http://kamojinja.web.fc2.com/kamojinja01.html History of Kamo Shrine] (official website).</ref>. As a result, the future {{ill|lt=Emperor Takakura|Q357261|qid=Q357261|1=Emperor Takakura}} was born, and to celebrate this, Mishima Shrine was founded at Gojozaka in Kyoto<ref name="ka2"/>. However, the place of her worship is recorded as “Mishima Shrine,” and there is also a theory that this refers to Mishima Kamo Shrine at Mishimae<ref name="ka2">[http://kamojinja.web.fc2.com/120504-02.html Kamo Shrine Newsletter] (official website).</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, the shrine was designated as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 46 ({{ill|lt=1971|Q2475|qid=Q2475|1=1971}}), the main hall and worship hall were newly constructed.

=== Court rank ===
* {{ill|lt=Gangyō|Q747451|qid=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 8 ({{ill|lt=884|Q23895|qid=Q23895|1=884}}), December 21: promoted from Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade to Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade (“{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}”) – recorded as “Mishima Shrine.” There is also a theory that this refers to {{ill|lt=Mishima Kamo Shrine|Q11355295|qid=Q11355295|1=Mishima-Kamo Shrine}}.

